>> How much do you
think it would cost

00:50:53.217 --> 00:50:57.254 align:middle line:84%
to completely insulate the
grid in the United States?

00:50:57.254 --> 00:51:02.893 align:middle line:84%
And I'm saying that because what
we wasted giving it to banks

00:51:02.893 --> 00:51:05.362 align:middle line:84%
and everything else,
the bailout...

00:51:05.362 --> 00:51:06.530 align:middle line:90%
>> Plus some groups in Egypt.

00:51:06.530 --> 00:51:08.599 align:middle line:90%
>> How much would it cost?

00:51:08.599 --> 00:51:11.201 align:middle line:84%
>> I've heard figures
as low as $50 billion.

00:51:11.201 --> 00:51:13.704 align:middle line:84%
>> Which is nothing in
the scheme of things.

00:51:13.704 --> 00:51:15.939 align:middle line:84%
>> Not compared to some
of the bills we've seen.

00:51:15.939 --> 00:51:20.911 align:middle line:84%
In terms of the survival of my
daughter, it's for you and me

00:51:20.911 --> 00:51:22.713 align:middle line:90%
and this audience to hear the --

00:51:22.713 --> 00:51:23.814 align:middle line:84%
what we've been throwing
[multiple voices] a billion

00:51:23.814 --> 00:51:25.182 align:middle line:90%
dollars on.

00:51:25.182 --> 00:51:27.451 align:middle line:84%
>> And to keep this country
intact and to minimize that kind

00:51:27.451 --> 00:51:31.855 align:middle line:84%
of an attack or that kind of
a catastrophe from the sun,

00:51:31.855 --> 00:51:35.058 align:middle line:84%
we would be a strong nation
if we were able to do this.

00:51:35.058 --> 00:51:37.761 align:middle line:84%
>> We're not going
to be 100% protected,

00:51:37.761 --> 00:51:41.231 align:middle line:84%
but if we can get a 50%
to 75% protection level

00:51:41.231 --> 00:51:43.267 align:middle line:84%
on our distribution
and transportation

00:51:43.267 --> 00:51:44.434 align:middle line:90%
and control systems...

00:51:44.434 --> 00:51:45.836 align:middle line:90%
>> Yes.

00:51:45.836 --> 00:51:48.238 align:middle line:84%
>> ...casualty figure would go
from -- think of it, George --

00:51:48.238 --> 00:51:52.876 align:middle line:84%
270 million Americans
dead in a year.

00:51:52.876 --> 00:51:57.681 align:middle line:84%
People wonder how the
figures seem so absurd.

00:51:57.681 --> 00:52:00.150 align:middle line:84%
I remember Dr. Pry -- he's
quite an expert on this --

00:52:00.150 --> 00:52:01.718 align:middle line:90%
said, "The old nuclear war

00:52:01.718 --> 00:52:03.520 align:middle line:84%
with the Russians would
have been more humane."

00:52:03.520 --> 00:52:05.489 align:middle line:84%
>> You know, when
you buy insurance...

00:52:05.489 --> 00:52:06.557 align:middle line:90%
>> That's a good one.

00:52:06.557 --> 00:52:08.425 align:middle line:84%
>> ...auto insurance,
house insurance...

00:52:08.425 --> 00:52:09.626 align:middle line:90%
>> Hmm-mm.

00:52:09.626 --> 00:52:12.829 align:middle line:84%
>> ...initially you think
what a waste of money...

00:52:12.829 --> 00:52:13.530 align:middle line:90%
>> Until you need it.

00:52:13.530 --> 00:52:15.032 align:middle line:90%
>> ...until you need it.

00:52:15.032 --> 00:52:19.536 align:middle line:84%
And the reason you buy
insurance is if you need it.

00:52:19.536 --> 00:52:22.539 align:middle line:84%
Isn't this a great
insurance policy?

00:52:22.539 --> 00:52:23.840 align:middle line:90%
Insulate the grid

00:52:23.840 --> 00:52:26.543 align:middle line:84%
>> Would a bank let you
buy a house without...

00:52:26.543 --> 00:52:27.110 align:middle line:90%
>> Without.

00:52:27.110 --> 00:52:27.744 align:middle line:90%
>> ...insurance?

00:52:27.744 --> 00:52:29.079 align:middle line:90%
>> Absolutely not.

00:52:29.079 --> 00:52:30.214 align:middle line:90%
>> And...

00:52:30.214 --> 00:52:31.715 align:middle line:84%
>> And they're pushing
earthquake insurance now

00:52:31.715 --> 00:52:33.116 align:middle line:90%
in California.

00:52:33.116 --> 00:52:34.952 align:middle line:84%
They know one day
they're going to get hit

00:52:34.952 --> 00:52:38.455 align:middle line:84%
and they want you
covered and protected.

00:52:38.455 --> 00:52:40.357 align:middle line:84%
So why don't we just
do it as a nation?

00:52:40.357 --> 00:52:43.393 align:middle line:84%
Why doesn't a presidential
candidate, when he's running --

00:52:43.393 --> 00:52:45.963 align:middle line:84%
I don't think anyone has ever
addressed this in a campaign.

00:52:45.963 --> 00:52:47.164 align:middle line:90%
>> Two candidates have.

00:52:47.164 --> 00:52:48.565 align:middle line:90%
>> Okay. Ron Paul?

00:52:48.565 --> 00:52:49.433 align:middle line:90%
>> And Newt Gingrich.

00:52:49.433 --> 00:52:50.834 align:middle line:90%
>> Okay.

00:52:50.834 --> 00:52:53.503 align:middle line:84%
>> Were the only two candidates
who talked about it on -- yes...

00:52:53.503 --> 00:52:55.439 align:middle line:84%
>> But the media
scoffed right over it.

00:52:55.439 --> 00:52:57.374 align:middle line:84%
>> Yeah. Let me give
you a different analogy.

00:52:57.374 --> 00:52:59.676 align:middle line:84%
I just bought a car for my
daughter a couple of years ago.

00:52:59.676 --> 00:53:00.911 align:middle line:84%
Of course I went
out and got a car

00:53:00.911 --> 00:53:02.145 align:middle line:90%
with a five star safety rating.

00:53:02.145 --> 00:53:03.513 align:middle line:90%
>> Sure.

00:53:03.513 --> 00:53:05.649 align:middle line:84%
>> What kind of father would
I be if I'm standing there

00:53:05.649 --> 00:53:07.618 align:middle line:84%
and the dealer says,
"Okay, the car is 12,000.

00:53:07.618 --> 00:53:08.886 align:middle line:90%
I said, well, do me a favor.

00:53:08.886 --> 00:53:10.020 align:middle line:90%
Take the airbags out.

00:53:10.020 --> 00:53:10.988 align:middle line:90%
>> Yeah.

00:53:10.988 --> 00:53:11.822 align:middle line:84%
>> Take the collapsible
column here.

00:53:11.822 --> 00:53:12.923 align:middle line:90%
>> Save me a little bit here.

00:53:12.923 --> 00:53:14.424 align:middle line:84%
>> You can save me a
couple of thousand bucks

00:53:14.424 --> 00:53:16.360 align:middle line:84%
if you get rid of
all this stuff.

00:53:16.360 --> 00:53:18.996 align:middle line:90%
What kind of father would I be?

00:53:18.996 --> 00:53:20.897 align:middle line:90%
I'm no, load it all in.

00:53:20.897 --> 00:53:23.634 align:middle line:84%
So for the cost of getting
a safe car for my daughter,

00:53:23.634 --> 00:53:27.437 align:middle line:84%
if we multiply that out across
the entire United States

00:53:27.437 --> 00:53:30.607 align:middle line:84%
to every household, we
would have a secure grid

00:53:30.607 --> 00:53:33.210 align:middle line:84%
which would protect my
daughter and your kids

00:53:33.210 --> 00:53:35.145 align:middle line:90%
and everybody's grandchildren.

00:53:35.145 --> 00:53:38.448 align:middle line:84%
>> I would create it as
a tax, not on people,

00:53:38.448 --> 00:53:40.150 align:middle line:90%
but on these companies...

00:53:40.150 --> 00:53:40.984 align:middle line:90%
>> Yes.

00:53:40.984 --> 00:53:42.319 align:middle line:90%
>> ...that provide the power.

00:53:42.319 --> 00:53:43.553 align:middle line:84%
And I would say,
"Look, you're going

00:53:43.553 --> 00:53:45.555 align:middle line:90%
to amortize this over 20 years."

00:53:45.555 --> 00:53:46.590 align:middle line:90%
>> Hmm-mm.

00:53:46.590 --> 00:53:47.357 align:middle line:84%
>> "But you're going
to pay for this."

00:53:47.357 --> 00:53:48.592 align:middle line:90%
>> Yes.

00:53:48.592 --> 00:53:50.594 align:middle line:84%
>> And we're going to do
this as a nation to insulate

00:53:50.594 --> 00:53:52.362 align:middle line:90%
and protect this country.

00:53:52.362 --> 00:53:56.867 align:middle line:84%
And I think that would be
brilliant because one day one

00:53:56.867 --> 00:54:00.570 align:middle line:84%
of these two possibilities
is going to occur.

00:54:00.570 --> 00:54:04.074 align:middle line:84%
>> I think of Admiral Halsey
coming into Pearl Harbor

00:54:04.074 --> 00:54:07.477 align:middle line:84%
on the evening of December
7th looking at the wreckage

00:54:07.477 --> 00:54:13.083 align:middle line:84%
of the American fleet with
his ship, the Enterprise --

00:54:13.083 --> 00:54:15.786 align:middle line:84%
description of the bodies
floating in the bay,

00:54:15.786 --> 00:54:17.621 align:middle line:90%
being pushed aside by this boat.

00:54:17.621 --> 00:54:19.289 align:middle line:90%
>> Yeah.

00:54:19.289 --> 00:54:22.726 align:middle line:84%
>> And I cannot quote exactly
what Admiral Halsey said he was

00:54:22.726 --> 00:54:24.795 align:middle line:84%
going to do before
this was done.

00:54:24.795 --> 00:54:27.564 align:middle line:84%
44 months later he was there
to take their surrender

00:54:27.564 --> 00:54:31.568 align:middle line:84%
in Tokyo Harbor with a
thousand ships behind him.

00:54:31.568 --> 00:54:33.704 align:middle line:84%
We will not have that
opportunity again

00:54:33.704 --> 00:54:34.771 align:middle line:90%
if we get hit by an EMP.

00:54:34.771 --> 00:54:38.175 align:middle line:84%
The game is over in
the first second.

00:54:38.175 --> 00:54:40.777 align:middle line:90%
>> If the sun sends off a CME...

00:54:40.777 --> 00:54:41.912 align:middle line:90%
>> Yes.

00:54:41.912 --> 00:54:43.280 align:middle line:84%
>> ...we've got a couple
days on that one, right?

00:54:43.280 --> 00:54:46.550 align:middle line:84%
>> Fortunately, a CME moves
slower than the speed of light.

00:54:46.550 --> 00:54:49.052 align:middle line:84%
I was up at Goddard
Labs last year talking

00:54:49.052 --> 00:54:51.088 align:middle line:90%
with their solar experts.

00:54:51.088 --> 00:54:52.689 align:middle line:90%
Has a remarkable crew.

00:54:52.689 --> 00:54:53.924 align:middle line:84%
They're dedicate
-- I asked them,

00:54:53.924 --> 00:54:57.027 align:middle line:84%
"If the big one is coming,
what do you guys do?"

00:54:57.027 --> 00:55:00.397 align:middle line:84%
And they said, "Our duty is
to be here and keep putting

00:55:00.397 --> 00:55:03.133 align:middle line:84%
out the information as long
as possible until it hits."

00:55:03.133 --> 00:55:04.634 align:middle line:90%
These are our top solar experts.

00:55:04.634 --> 00:55:05.802 align:middle line:90%
I said, "And then what?"

00:55:05.802 --> 00:55:07.304 align:middle line:84%
>> And we've had
episodes already.

00:55:07.304 --> 00:55:08.405 align:middle line:90%
I've received notices...

00:55:08.405 --> 00:55:09.606 align:middle line:90%
>> Of course.

00:55:09.606 --> 00:55:11.975 align:middle line:84%
>> ...during my show that
we might have disruption

00:55:11.975 --> 00:55:15.245 align:middle line:84%
with broadcasting
from smaller flares...

00:55:15.245 --> 00:55:15.912 align:middle line:90%
>> Right.

00:55:15.912 --> 00:55:16.947 align:middle line:90%
>> ...that take off.

00:55:16.947 --> 00:55:18.482 align:middle line:84%
So the big ones, you
know, we have a --

00:55:18.482 --> 00:55:21.184 align:middle line:84%
we'd have two days to
do a little preparing.

00:55:21.184 --> 00:55:23.587 align:middle line:84%
But that's why we should
be preparing right now.

00:55:23.587 --> 00:55:26.723 align:middle line:84%
>> And see, right there you
hit another point: preparing.

00:55:26.723 --> 00:55:30.560 align:middle line:84%
We have not run even a
simulation drill, let alone --

00:55:30.560 --> 00:55:32.629 align:middle line:90%
I remember one candidate saying,

00:55:32.629 --> 00:55:34.664 align:middle line:84%
"We should get a
moderate size town

00:55:34.664 --> 00:55:36.400 align:middle line:90%
in America to do a simulation."

00:55:36.400 --> 00:55:37.401 align:middle line:90%
>> Shut the power down.

00:55:37.401 --> 00:55:38.769 align:middle line:84%
>> ...to shut the
whole grid down...

00:55:38.769 --> 00:55:42.606 align:middle line:84%
>> Yeah. And have the media
there, everybody recording this,

00:55:42.606 --> 00:55:47.043 align:middle line:84%
showing you what happens to
life if power's down for a --

00:55:47.043 --> 00:55:48.311 align:middle line:90%
oh, yeah, I would take care

00:55:48.311 --> 00:55:50.614 align:middle line:84%
of the hospitals and
things like that.

00:55:50.614 --> 00:55:55.085 align:middle line:84%
But I would monitor people
almost like  The Truman Show.

00:55:55.085 --> 00:55:58.522 align:middle line:84%
And just watch them and how
they live, and how they react,

00:55:58.522 --> 00:55:59.923 align:middle line:90%
while this is going on.

00:55:59.923 --> 00:56:02.225 align:middle line:84%
And I think it would
be startling...

00:56:02.225 --> 00:56:03.360 align:middle line:90%
>> I think anybody...

00:56:03.360 --> 00:56:04.294 align:middle line:90%
>> ...the end results.

00:56:04.294 --> 00:56:05.562 align:middle line:84%
>> ...old enough
in the audience --

00:56:05.562 --> 00:56:08.131 align:middle line:84%
because I remember just before
the Cuban Missile Crisis

00:56:08.131 --> 00:56:10.634 align:middle line:84%
in [inaudible] where
we did simulate.

00:56:10.634 --> 00:56:11.868 align:middle line:90%
>> We used to have those...

00:56:11.868 --> 00:56:13.203 align:middle line:90%
>> Duck and cover.

00:56:13.203 --> 00:56:16.006 align:middle line:84%
>> ...those duck and cover
alerts in school and everything

00:56:16.006 --> 00:56:18.975 align:middle line:84%
and we got to sit down, or
go to a fallout shelter.

00:56:18.975 --> 00:56:19.843 align:middle line:90%
>> Hmm-mm.

00:56:19.843 --> 00:56:21.378 align:middle line:84%
>> I remember my
neighbor growing

00:56:21.378 --> 00:56:22.979 align:middle line:84%
up in Dearborn Heights,
Michigan.

00:56:22.979 --> 00:56:25.382 align:middle line:84%
He built a fallout
shelter in his basement,

00:56:25.382 --> 00:56:27.384 align:middle line:90%
